\section{Conclusions and Future Work}
\label{sec:conclusion}
In this paper, we presented the G\textendash DS3 Transformer, a novel architecture that integrates the Structured State Space Duality framework with an adaptive, data\textendash dependent gating mechanism. By dynamically interpolating between efficient linear state updates and more expressive state evolution, our approach effectively addresses the challenge of balancing hardware efficiency and expressivity in long\textendash sequence modeling. Experimental evaluations on synthetic copy\textendash memory tasks, efficiency benchmarks, and ablation studies indicate that G\textendash DS3 achieves competitive training losses and maintains predictable scaling in inference latency, all while operating with a lightweight computational footprint. The active engagement of the gating mechanism confirms its role in enhancing model adaptivity under varying input complexities. Future research will focus on extending the G\textendash DS3 approach to non\textendash causal variants, exploring more expressive gating strategies, and integrating additional MLP and attention components to further bolster the architecture's flexibility. Overall, the G\textendash DS3 Transformer represents a promising step forward in scalable and adaptive sequence modeling.

